B.a3g=s(["Abductor Pollicis Brevis (APB)","First Dorsal Interosseous (FDI)","Opponens Pollicis","Flexor Carpi Ulnaris"],t.s)
B.ah_=new A.b0("Which muscle is the most distal innervated by the Ulnar nerve and is essential for evaluating Froment's sign?",B.a3g,1,"The FIRST DORSAL INTEROSSEOUS (FDI) is the most distal muscle innervated by the ulnar nerve. Weakness here results in Froment's sign, where the patient must substitute the median-innervated FPL for pinching. Sampling FDI is mandatory to differentiate ulnar entrapment at Guyon's canal from lower radiculopathies.")
B.a1W=s(["Sampling the Adductor Pollicis","Overshooting into the Opponens Pollicis","Hitting the Radial Artery","Entering the Flexor Pollicis Longus"],t.s)
B.ahz=new A.b0("When sampling the Abductor Pollicis Brevis (APB), what is a common technical pitfall if the needle is inserted too deeply?",B.a1W,1,"If you insert the needle too deeply (beyond 1/2 inch) in the thenar eminence, you will overshoot the superficial APB and inadvertently sample the deeper OPPONENS POLLICIS muscle. Precise shallow depth is required for APB.")
B.a_X=s(["Extensor Digitorum Communis","Extensor Indicis Proprius (EIP)","Brachioradialis","Extensor Carpi Radialis Longus"],t.s)
B.agx=new A.b0("Which muscle is the 'ultimate test' to rule out a distal radial nerve injury, such as Posterior Interosseous Nerve (PIN) entrapment at the Arcade of Frohse?",B.a_X,1,"The EXTENSOR INDICIS PROPRIUS (EIP) is usually the most distal muscle innervated by the radial nerve complex. It is the definitive muscle to evaluate when ruling out distal PIN entrapment or Saturday night palsy.")
B.a4B=s(["Flexor Digitorum Superficialis","Pronator Teres (PT)","Flexor Carpi Radialis","Palmaris Longus"],t.s)
B.ahC=new A.b0("To differentiate a high Median nerve injury from Carpal Tunnel Syndrome, which proximal forearm muscle should be sampled?",B.a4B,1,"The PRONATOR TERES (PT) is the most proximal forearm muscle innervated by the median nerve. Because the nerve passes through its two heads, sampling it helps localize entrapment (Pronator Teres Syndrome) vs distal wrist entrapment.")
B.a28=s(["Long Head","Medial Head","Lateral Head","All are equally safe"],t.s)
B.agA=new A.b0("In cases of a suspected C7 radiculopathy, which head of the triceps is generally considered the safest and easiest to sample?",B.a28,2,"The LATERAL HEAD of the triceps is preferred for routine evaluation. It is critical for C7 isolation; its innervation branches so high in the axilla that it is spared in 'Saturday night palsy' radial nerve compressions at the spiral groove.")
B.a2I=s(["Tibialis Anterior","Extensor Hallucis Longus (EHL)","Peroneus Longus","Gastrocnemius"],t.s)
B.agQ=new A.b0("Which muscle allows for clear differentiation between an L5 radiculopathy and an isolated Peroneal (Fibular) neuropathy because of its Strong L5-S1 representation?",B.a2I,1,"While Tibialis Anterior is primarily L4-L5, the EXTENSOR HALLUCIS LONGUS (EHL) has a stronger L5-S1 representation. This makes EHL an excellent target to differentiate L5 radiculopathy from isolated peroneal nerve injury.")
B.a_T=s(["Inability to jump","Foot drop (loss of dorsiflexion)","Inability to wiggle toes","Severe calf cramping"],t.s)
B.ahw=new A.b0("What is the hallmark clinical sign of severe denervation in the Tibialis Anterior muscle?",B.a_T,1,"The TIBIALIS ANTERIOR is the king of foot dorsiflexion. Damage to the deep peroneal nerve or L5 root causes 'FOOT DROP', forcing a high-stepping gait to avoid tripping.")
B.a08=s(["Soleus","Flexor Hallucis Longus","Tibialis Posterior","Medial Gastrocnemius"],t.s)
B.agK=new A.b0("Which muscle is the deepest and most difficult to reach in the posterior leg compartment, but is critical for evaluating L5 root integrity via the Tibial nerve?",B.a08,2,"The TIBIALIS POSTERIOR is the deepest muscle in the posterior compartment. It is heavily innervated by the L5 root via the Tibial nerve, making it a key discriminator for complex lumbosacral plexopathies.")
B.a6l=s(["Hitting the Sural nerve","Injury to the Posterior Tibial Artery/Nerve bundle","Damaging the Achilles tendon","Overshooting into the Fibula"],t.s)
B.ah3=new A.b0("What is the primary danger when attempting to sample the Tibialis Posterior muscle?",B.a6l,1,"When sampling Tibialis Posterior, the major neurovascular bundle (POSTERIOR TIBIAL ARTERY and NERVE) lies very close. Clinicians must stay tight to the posterior cortex of the tibia and avoid indiscriminate lateral movements.")
B.a3D=s(["Rectus Femoris","Vastus Medialis","Vastus Lateralis","Biceps Femoris"],t.s)
B.ahn=new A.b0("Which muscle is the primary shock absorber/extensor of the knee and is the largest component of the quadriceps?",B.a3D,2,"The VASTUS LATERALIS is the largest of the quadriceps. If the Femoral nerve is damaged, the patient loses the ability to lock their knee in extension, causing life-altering instability during walking.")
B.a1H=s([B.ah_,B.ahz,B.agx,B.ahC,B.agA,B.agQ,B.ahw,B.agK,B.ah3,B.ahn],t.hB)
B.ahE=new A.mb(B.a1H,"Needle Mastery","Validate your anatomical precision and technical knowledge.",null)
B.a6y=s(["Carpal Tunnel","Median Nerve at the Elbow","C6 Nerve Root","Brachial Plexus"],t.s)
B.agE=new A.b0("A patient presents with numbness in the thumb and index finger. The Median SNAP (sensory) is completely normal, but the Biceps and Brachioradialis show denervation. Where is the lesion?",B.a6y,2,"This is a classic C6 radiculopathy. The clue is the NORMAL sensory study (SNAP) despite the numbness\u2014this means the pinch is 'Behind the DRG'. The involvement of both the Biceps and Brachioradialis confirms the level.")
B.a4u=s(["To let the pain subside","To allow enough time for fibrillation potentials to develop in the limbs","Because insurance won't pay for it sooner","To allow the disc to heal on its own"],t.s)
B.ahg=new A.b0("Why do we wait at least 3 weeks after a sudden disc herniation before doing a full EMG study?",B.a4u,1,"Wallerian degeneration takes time. It takes approximately 2-3 weeks for the distal parts of the nerve in the limbs to show spontaneous activity (fibrillations) after a proximal injury at the root.")
B.a4j=s(["Tibialis Anterior","Extensor Hallucis Longus","Gluteus Medius","Gastroc"],t.s)
B.ahD=new A.b0("Which muscle should you check to differentiate an L5 radiculopathy from a Peroneal (Fibular) neuropathy?",B.a4j,2,"The Gluteus Medius is innervated by the Superior Gluteal Nerve (L5), which branches off the plexus BEFORE the peroneal nerve forms. If the Glut Med is abnormal, the lesion must be at or proximal to the plexus/root level.")
B.a2p=s(["Spinal stenosis","Degenerative spondylosis","Herniated nucleus pulposus (disc herniation)","Malignancy"],t.s)
B.agM=new A.b0("What is the most common cause of radiculopathy in a 35-year-old patient?",B.a2p,2,"In patients YOUNGER than 50 years, HERNIATED NUCLEUS PULPOSUS is the most common cause. In patients OLDER than 50, SPINAL STENOSIS becomes more prevalent.")
B.a21=s(["Achilles reflex","Patellar reflex","Biceps reflex","Medial hamstring reflex"],t.s)
B.ahu=new A.b0("Which reflex is associated with L4 radiculopathy?",B.a21,1,"L4 radiculopathy affects the PATELLAR (knee jerk) reflex. The reflex patterns are: L4 = patellar, L5 = medial hamstring, S1 = Achilles.")
B.a14=s(["Disc herniation","Spinal stenosis","Inflammatory radiculitis","Athletic injury"],t.s)
B.agH=new A.b0("A 60-year-old patient presents with progressive back pain and bilateral leg weakness. What is the most likely etiology?",B.a14,1,"In older patients, spinal stenosis due to degenerative changes is the leading cause, often presenting with bilateral symptoms.")
B.a6w=s(["0-5%","10-30%","50-70%","90-100%"],t.s)
B.ah4=new A.b0("What percentage of radiculopathy cases may have paraspinal abnormalities as the ONLY EMG finding?",B.a6w,1,"Paraspinal abnormalities are found as the sole indicator in 10-30% of cases, making paraspinal examination crucial for root localization.")
B.a5m=s(["EMG timeline","Myotomal patterns","Non-mechanical causes","Reflex associations"],t.s)
B.agZ=new A.b0("What does the 'HI MADAM' mnemonic help remember?",B.a5m,2,"'HI MADAM' covers non-mechanical causes like Herpes, Inflammatory, Metastasis, Arachnoiditis, Diabetes, Abscess, and Mass.")
B.a1P=s(["C5","C6","C7","C8"],t.s)
B.ahB=new A.b0("Which nerve root is most commonly affected in cervical radiculopathy?",B.a1P,2,"C7 is the most commonly affected cervical nerve root (approx 70%), usually presenting with triceps weakness.")
B.a69=s(["Weakness of ankle dorsiflexion","Loss of patellar reflex","Loss of Achilles reflex","Sensory loss on the medial calf"],t.s)
B.agO=new A.b0("In an S1 radiculopathy, which finding is most expected?",B.a69,2,"S1 radiculopathy classically presents with LOSS OF THE ACHILLES REFLEX and plantar flexion weakness.")
B.a42=s(["Ulnar neuropathy at the elbow","Combined median and ulnar neuropathy","C8 radiculopathy","Lower trunk brachial plexopathy"],t.s)
B.ahi=new A.b0("A patient presents with weakness of finger abduction (FDI) and thumb opposition (APB). SNAPs are all normal. EMG shows fibrillations in FDI, APB, EIP, and C8 paraspinals. What is the most likely diagnosis?",B.a42,2,"Normal SNAPs rule out a postganglionic lesion. The involvement of ulnar (FDI), median (APB), AND radial (EIP) muscles sharing the C8 root, plus C8 paraspinal fibrillations, localizes to the C8 nerve root.")
B.a4D=s(["Yes -- reduced recruitment proves radiculopathy","No -- fibrillations take 2-3 weeks to develop; repeat at 3-4 weeks","Yes -- absence of fibrillations rules out radiculopathy","No -- the patient should never have EMG after disc herniation"],t.s)
B.ah8=new A.b0("A patient had a lumbar disc herniation 5 days ago. You perform an EMG and find no fibrillations anywhere, but recruitment is mildly reduced in the tibialis anterior. Is this study reliable?",B.a4D,1,"At day 5, Wallerian degeneration has barely begun. Fibrillation potentials take 2-3 weeks to appear in proximal muscles and 3-5 weeks in distal muscles. The optimal timing for EMG is 3-4 weeks post-onset.")
B.a77=s([B.agE,B.ahg,B.ahD,B.agM,B.ahu,B.agH,B.ah4,B.agZ,B.ahB,B.agO,B.ahi,B.ah8],t.hB)
B.ahG=new A.mb(B.a77,"Radiculopathy Mastery","Test your skills in root-level localization.",null)
B.a4U=s(["Myasthenia Gravis","Motor Neuron Disease (ALS)","Polymyositis","Myotonic Dystrophy"],t.s)
B.ahm=new A.b0("Which clinical diagnosis typically presents on EMG with widespread active denervation, large reinnervation MUAPs, and fasciculations?",B.a4U,1,"Widespread denervation + Reinnervation (Large MUAPs) + Fasciculations is the classic triad for Motor Neuron Disease (ALS).")
B.a6X=s(["Seashell sound","Rain on tin roof","Marching soldiers","Dive bomber"],t.s)
B.agm=new A.b0("What is the characteristic sound of fibrillation potentials on EMG?",B.a6X,1,"Fibrillations fire regularly at 0.5-10Hz, creating a characteristic 'rain on tin roof' sound.")
B.a7f=s(["Always normal","Only seen in myopathy","Associated with radiation plexopathy or MS","Indicates severe stroke"],t.s)
B.agG=new A.b0("What is the clinical significance of myokymic discharges?",B.a7f,2,"Myokymic discharges (grouped repetitive MUAP firing) are classic for radiation damage or MS (facial).")
B.a3S=s(["Endplate: initial negative; Fibrillation: initial positive","Endplate: initial positive; Fibrillation: initial negative","Amplitude size","Firing rate"],t.s)
B.ags=new A.b0("How do you distinguish normal endplate spikes from pathologic fibrillations?",B.a3S,0,"Endplate spikes are negative onset (upward) because they are nerve terminal irritation; Pathologic denervation is positive onset (downward) because it starts at the muscle fiber.")
B.a1t=s(["Fasciculations","Complex Repetitive Discharges","Myotonic Discharges","CRPS"],t.s)
B.ahf=new A.b0("Which EMG pattern is defined by a 'dive bomber' sound and waxing/waning frequency?",B.a1t,2,"Myotonic discharges wax and wane in both frequency and amplitude, creating the 'dive bomber' or 'revving engine' sound.")
B.a4M=s(["Rain on tin roof","Corn popping","Machine gun","Waterfall"],t.s)
B.ahs=new A.b0("Fasciculations sound similar to:",B.a4M,1,"Fasciculations are single motor units firing irregularly, sounding like 'popcorn' or 'corn popping'.")
B.a3n=s(["2","3","4","5"],t.s)
B.ahp=new A.b0("A 'polyphasic' motor unit potential is defined as having more than how many phases?",B.a3n,2,"A MUAP is polyphasic if it has more than 4 phases (where phases = baseline crossings + 1).")
B.a2c=s(["Reduced (fast firing)","Early (full interference at low force)","Normal","Infinite"],t.s)
B.ah6=new A.b0("In a patient with severe myopathy, what recruitment pattern is expected?",B.a2c,1,"In myopathy, since each unit is weak, the CNS activates many more units early to compensate for low force.")
B.a5u=s(["0.5-10 Hz","50-100 Hz","150-300 Hz","1000 Hz"],t.s)
B.agX=new A.b0("Neuromyotonic discharges fire at what frequency range?",B.a5u,2,"Neuromyotonic discharges are very high frequency (150-300 Hz) decrementing bursts.")
B.a2M=s(["Fibrillations","Fasciculations","Complex Repetitive Discharges (CRDs)","Myotonia"],t.s)
B.ah9=new A.b0("What spontaneous activity pattern sounds like a 'machine-like' motorcycle or motorboat due to its perfect regularity?",B.a2M,2,"CRDs are perfectly regular and start/stop abruptly, sounding like a 'motorcycle' or 'motorboat'.")
B.a3q=s(["Single muscle fiber","A single motor unit","A nerve bundle","A spinal cord segment"],t.s)
B.agI=new A.b0("Fasciculation potentials represent the spontaneous firing of what structure?",B.a3q,1,"Fasciculations are the spontaneous firing of an entire motor unit, whereas fibrillations are firing of single muscle fibers.")
B.a6o=s([B.ahm,B.agm,B.agG,B.ags,B.ahf,B.ahs,B.ahp,B.ah6,B.agX,B.ah9,B.agI],t.hB)
B.ahH=new A.mb(B.a6o,"Pattern Recognition Mastery","Challenge your visual and auditory diagnostic skills.",null)
B.a2m=s(["Upper Trunk","Lateral Cord","C6 Nerve Root","Median Nerve at the wrist"],t.s)
B.agn=new A.b0("A patient presents with numbness in the thumb and index finger (C6 distribution). The Median SNAP (recording Digit 2) is normal. Where is the most likely location of the lesion?",B.a2m,2,"If the SNAP is NORMAL in a region of numbness, the lesion is PRE-GANGLIONIC (a nerve root). Post-ganglionic lesions (Plexus/Nerve) destroy the sensory axons distal to the DRG, causing a drop in SNAP amplitude.")
B.a2j=s(["Lower Trunk Brachial Plexopathy","C8/T1 Nerve Root Avulsion","Ulnar Neuropathy at the Cubital Tunnel","Neurogenic Thoracic Outlet Syndrome"],t.s)
B.agW=new A.b0("A patient presents with a 'Claw Hand' and severe hand intrinsic weakness. You also note Miosis and Ptosis on the same side (Horner's Syndrome). This strongly localizes to:",B.a2j,1,"Horner's Syndrome + C8/T1 symptoms indicates a PRE-GANGLIONIC (root) lesion high enough to involve the sympathetic rami. This usually suggests a traumatic pre-ganglionic root avulsion.")
B.a5y=s(["Supraspinatus","Deltoid","Rhomboids (Dorsal Scapular Nerve)","Biceps"],t.s)
B.agl=new A.b0("Which muscle is supplied by a branch directly off the C5 root, making it a critical 'Root vs. Trunk' discriminator on EMG?",B.a5y,2,"The Rhomboids are innervated by the Dorsal Scapular Nerve, which branches directly off the C5 ROOT. If Rhomboids are spared but the Supraspinatus (Upper Trunk) is weak, the lesion must be at the Trunk level.")
B.a7c=s(["Pancoast Tumor",u.i,"Acute C5 Radiculopathy","Axillary Nerve Entrapment"],t.s)
B.agS=new A.b0("A patient presents with sudden, intense, 'unbearable' shoulder pain that lasts for a week, followed by progressive weakness in the shoulder and serratus anterior. This is characteristic of:",B.a7c,1,"Sudden severe pain followed by multi-focal weakness (often including the Long Thoracic Nerve causing winging) is the hallmark of Parsonage-Turner Syndrome.")
B.a1l=s(["Upper Trunk; Median SNAP drop","Lower Trunk; Median CMAP drop + Ulnar SNAP drop","Cords; Normal SNAPs","Roots; Fasciculations"],t.s)
B.agu=new A.b0("Neurogenic Thoracic Outlet Syndrome (nTOS) classically affects which part of the plexus and leads to which EMG finding?",B.a1l,1,"nTOS (Gilliatt-Sumner hand) involves the Lower Trunk. It is unique because it shows a Median CMAP drop (loss of thenar fibers) and an Ulnar SNAP drop (loss of T1/C8 sensory fibers).")
B.a7l=s(["Lateral Cord","Medial Cord","Posterior Cord","Terminal Cord"],t.s)
B.ahd=new A.b0("Which cord of the brachial plexus is formed solely by the combination of the posterior divisions of all three trunks?",B.a7l,2,"The Posterior Cord is unique as it receives input from all three trunks (Upper, Middle, and Lower) via their posterior divisions.")
B.a4_=s(["C8-T1; Claw Hand","C5-C6; Waiter's Tip","C7; Wrist Drop","C5-T1; Flail Arm"],t.s)
B.agF=new A.b0("An 'Erb's Palsy' typically involves which roots and results in what classic limb posture?",B.a4_,1,"Erb's palsy involves the Upper Trunk (C5-C6). Loss of abductors and external rotators results in the arm being adducted and internally rotated (Waiter's Tip).")
B.a2X=s(["Abductor Pollicis Brevis","First Dorsal Interosseous","Biceps Brachii","Extensor Indicis Proprius"],t.s)
B.agD=new A.b0("During reinnervation after a severe global plexus injury, which of these muscles will show recovery FIRST?",B.a2X,2,"Nerves regrow at ~1mm/day. Muscles closest to the plexus (proximal, like the Biceps) will receive axons and show recovery long before distal hand muscles.")
B.a5F=s(["Radial Nerve","Axillary Nerve","Musculocutaneous Nerve","Thoracodorsal Nerve"],t.s)
B.aho=new A.b0("A lesion strictly localized to the Posterior Cord would spare which of these nerves?",B.a5F,2,"The Musculocutaneous nerve originates from the Lateral Cord. The Posterior Cord gives rise to the Radial, Axillary, Subscapular, and Thoracodorsal nerves.")
B.a4R=s(["Medial Cord / Lower Trunk","Lateral Cord","C6 Radiculopathy","Ulnar nerve at the elbow"],t.s)
B.ahy=new A.b0("You find low SNAPs in the Medial Antebrachial Cutaneous (MAC) and Ulnar distributions, but a normal Median SNAP (Digit 2). This geographic pattern localizes to:",B.a4R,0,"MAC and Ulnar SNAPs both represent the C8-T1/Medial Cord/Lower Trunk pathway. Sparing of the Median SNAP (C6-C7/Lateral Cord) confirms the geographic boundary.")
B.a2B=s(["FDI (Ulnar)","APB (Median)","ADM (Ulnar)","EIP (Radial)"],t.s)
B.ahj=new A.b0("What is the primary recording site for motor NCS in a suspected case of neurogenic Thoracic Outlet Syndrome?",B.a2B,1,"While nTOS is a lower trunk/medial cord issue, the fibers to the APB (Median) are often more selectively lost, leading to the characteristic thenar atrophy (Gilliatt-Sumner hand).")
B.a2C=s(["Ligament of Struthers","Pronator teres","Carpal tunnel","Axilla"],t.s)
B.agU=new A.b0("A patient has numbness in the thumb, index, and middle fingers with thenar weakness. What is the most common site of median nerve entrapment?",B.a2C,2,"Carpal tunnel syndrome is the most common peripheral nerve entrapment worldwide. The median nerve passes beneath the transverse carpal ligament with the flexor tendons. Thenar weakness (APB) plus sensory loss in the first 3.5 digits is the classic pattern.")
B.a4v=s(["Guyon's canal at the wrist","Cubital tunnel at the elbow","Medial cord of brachial plexus","C8 nerve root"],t.s)
B.agP=new A.b0("A patient has numbness in the small finger and weakness of finger abduction. The dorsal ulnar hand is also numb. Where is the lesion?",B.a4v,1,"The dorsal ulnar cutaneous nerve branches PROXIMAL to Guyon's canal. If dorsal ulnar hand sensation is abnormal, the lesion must be at or above the elbow (cubital tunnel). Guyon's canal lesions spare dorsal sensation because that branch has already departed.")
B.a35=s(["Axilla","Spiral groove of the humerus","Posterior interosseous nerve","Superficial radial nerve"],t.s)
B.agB=new A.b0("A patient wakes up after sleeping with the arm draped over a chair. They have wrist drop but can extend the elbow normally. Where is the radial nerve injured?",B.a35,1,"This is classic 'Saturday Night Palsy.' The radial nerve is compressed at the spiral groove. The triceps is spared because its branch exits proximal to the groove.")
B.a4Y=s(["Biceps brachii","Brachialis","Coracobrachialis","Deltoid"],t.s)
B.agp=new A.b0("The musculocutaneous nerve has a unique anatomical feature. Which muscle does it physically pierce (pass through)?",B.a4Y,2,"The musculocutaneous nerve (C5-C7, lateral cord) uniquely pierces through the coracobrachialis muscle before innervating the biceps and brachialis. It then continues as the purely sensory lateral antebrachial cutaneous nerve.")
B.a_L=s(["Radial nerve -- posterior forearm","Musculocutaneous nerve -- lateral forearm","Axillary nerve -- regimental badge area","Suprascapular nerve -- posterior shoulder"],t.s)
B.agY=new A.b0("A patient sustains an anterior shoulder dislocation. Which nerve is most at risk, and what is the key sensory area to test?",B.a_L,2,"The axillary nerve (C5-C6, posterior cord) wraps around the surgical neck of the humerus through the quadrilateral space. Anterior shoulder dislocations stretch or compress the nerve. Test sensation over the lateral deltoid ('regimental badge' area).")
B.a7h=s(["Greater sciatic foramen","Piriformis muscle","Popliteal fossa","Fibular head"],t.s)
B.ah5=new A.b0("The sciatic nerve bifurcates into its two terminal branches at which anatomical landmark?",B.a7h,2,"The sciatic nerve (L4-S3) typically divides into the tibial nerve and common fibular (peroneal) nerve at or just above the popliteal fossa behind the knee. In approximately 10-15% of individuals, the division occurs higher.")
B.a6u=s(["Sinus tarsi","Tarsal tunnel","Cuboid tunnel","Plantar fascia"],t.s)
B.agR=new A.b0("The tibial nerve passes through which structure at the ankle, analogous to the carpal tunnel at the wrist?",B.a6u,1,"The tarsal tunnel is formed by the flexor retinaculum behind the medial malleolus. The tibial nerve passes through this space. Compression here causes tarsal tunnel syndrome with burning pain and numbness on the plantar surface of the foot.")
B.a0F=s(["It crosses over bone with minimal soft tissue protection","It passes through a tight muscular tunnel","It has poor blood supply at this location","It divides into multiple branches here"],t.s)
B.agt=new A.b0("Why is the common fibular (peroneal) nerve particularly vulnerable to injury at the fibular head?",B.a0F,0,"The common fibular nerve wraps around the fibular neck just beneath the skin with almost no cushioning from muscle or fat. This makes it the most commonly injured nerve in the lower extremity. Compression from leg crossing, casts, or prolonged bed rest can cause foot drop.")
B.a1w=s(["Obturator nerve","Sciatic nerve","Femoral nerve","L3 nerve root"],t.s)
B.agq=new A.b0("A patient cannot extend the knee and has an absent patellar reflex. Sensation is reduced on the anterior thigh and medial leg. Which nerve is affected?",B.a1w,2,"The femoral nerve (L2-L4) innervates the quadriceps (knee extension), and its terminal sensory branch (saphenous nerve) supplies the medial leg. The patellar reflex is mediated by the femoral nerve (L3-L4). Common causes include retroperitoneal hematoma and post-surgical injury.")
B.a0f=s(["Greater sciatic foramen","Obturator foramen/canal","Inguinal canal","Femoral triangle"],t.s)
B.ahr=new A.b0("The obturator nerve exits the pelvis through which anatomical structure?",B.a0f,1,"The obturator nerve (L2-L4) exits through the obturator canal in the pelvis to reach the medial thigh. It innervates the adductor muscles. Obturator neuropathy can occur from pelvic fractures, hip surgery, or obturator hernia.")
B.a71=s(["Tibial and femoral nerves","Common fibular and tibial nerves","Saphenous and tibial nerves","Superficial and deep fibular nerves"],t.s)
B.ahh=new A.b0("The sural nerve is a purely sensory nerve formed by contributions from which two sources?",B.a71,1,"The sural nerve is formed by the medial sural cutaneous nerve (from the tibial nerve) joining the sural communicating branch (from the common fibular nerve) in the mid-calf. It is the gold standard reference nerve for diagnosing polyneuropathy.")
B.a1d=s(["Test Abductor Pollicis Brevis (APB)","Test Extensor Indicis (EI)","Test First Dorsal Interosseous (FDI)","Test Pronator Teres (PT)"],t.s)
B.ahv=new A.b0("How do you confidently differentiate a Lower Trunk (C8-T1) plexopathy from a Medial Cord plexopathy using needle EMG?",B.a1d,1,"Both Lower Trunk and Medial Cord lesions affect C8-T1 ulnar/median muscles (like APB and FDI). However, the Lower Trunk ALSO sends C8 fibers to the Radial Nerve via the Posterior Cord. Finding denervation in a C8 Radial muscle like Extensor Indicis proves the lesion is at the Lower Trunk, not the Medial Cord.")
