a6=A.ci("Wartenberg's Syndrome",a8,d4,"INDICATED (To rule out higher lesions)",A.a([A.u(!1,f0,f0,f0,f0,f0,"Extensor Indicis Proprius (EIP)",x3,f0,f0,i0,f0),A.u(!1,f0,f0,f0,f0,f0,x4,x3,f0,f0,i0,f0),A.u(!1,f0,f0,f0,f0,f0,u9,h9,f0,f0,v2,f0),A.u(!1,h7,f0,f0,f0,f0,"First Dorsal Interosseous (FDI)",h6,f0,f0,h1,f0),A.u(!1,h7,f0,f0,f0,f0,g9,h0,f0,f0,h1,f0),A.u(!1,h7,f0,f0,f0,f0,w2,h0,f0,f0,o8,f0)],n),"Wartenberg's Syndrome is a pure sensory neuropathy of the superficial radial nerve at the wrist. It is often caused by external compression (tight watches, handcuffs, casts). The hallmark is **sensory loss/pain in the snuffbox** with **strictly normal motor function**. Electrodiagnostically, the **Radial Sensory SNAP is abnormal** (low amplitude or absent) while the motor NCS and EMG are completely normal.",a7,"wartenberg",a9,ae8,ae7,!0,a6,A.a(["Wartenberg's syndrome is a pure sensory entrapment of the superficial radial nerve at the wrist.","Often confused with De Quervain's tenosynovitis; look for the neurological distribution of numbness and the abnormal SNAP to differentiate.","The hallmark is **Normal EMG** and **Abnormal Radial Sensory SNAP**.","Commonly caused by tight-fitting objects around the wrist ('Handcuff Palsy')."],af3),"Tingling on the Back of the Thumb")
ae7=A.ch(24,"Deep, poorly localized dull ache in the right shoulder and weakness when serving",i1,"Develop pain in the posterior shoulder over several months. Lately, notices he cannot 'follow through' on his serve and feels like his arm is 'giving out' during external rotation. No history of acute trauma. No neck pain or radiating numbness.",x1,"Professional Volleyball Player",i4)
ae8=A.cm("Visible wasting/atrophy of the right supraspinatus and infraspinatus fossae. Deltoid bulk is preserved.","Tenderness over the suprascapular notch (posterior scapula). No joint instability.","Symmetric 2+ throughout (Biceps, Triceps, Brachioradialis).","Full passive ROM. Pain with extreme horizontal adduction.","NORMAL throughout the arm, including the lateral shoulder (axillary patch) and all digital distributions.","Negative Empty Can test (no pain, just weakness). Negative Spurling's maneuver.","Right Shoulder Abduction (initial 15-30 degrees) 3/5. External Rotation (Infraspinatus) 2/5. Shoulder Abduction (Mid-range, Deltoid) 5/5. Biceps 5/5. Triceps 5/5.")
a9=A.a([A.Y("Suprascapular Nerve Entrapment (Suprascapular Notch)",d9),A.Y("Spinoglenoid Notch Entrapment","Entrapment at the spinoglenoid notch would involve ONLY the Infraspinatus, sparing the Supraspinatus. Here, both muscles are weak and atrophied."),A.Y(u0,"Radiculopathy would involve the Deltoid (Axillary), Biceps (Musculocutaneous), and Rhomboids/Paraspinals. It would also often be associated with neck pain and an abnormal Biceps reflex."),A.Y(y5,"Would involve a wider array of C5-C6 muscles including the Deltoid, Biceps, and Brachioradialis, and would typically have sensory loss in the lateral arm/forearm."),A.Y("Parsonage-Turner Syndrome (PTS)","PTS usually presents with a hyperacute, agonizing pain followed by weakness; this case is a chronic, progressive presentation related to overhead sports.")],ae9)
